05965nam a22009615i 9780674063105DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2011    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740631057 a10.4159/harvard.97806740631052doi  a(DE-B1597)178117  a(OCoLC)767858309  a(OCoLC)840446503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a809.93353222  aEC 54102rvk1 aMartens, Lorna, eauthor.14aThe Promise of Memory :bChildhood Recollection and Its Objects in Literary Modernism /cLorna Martens. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Writing Childhood Memory -- t1. Constructing Buried Trea sure: Proust's Childhood Memories -- t2. Making Things Out of Fear: Rilke and Childhood Memory -- t3. Collecting the Past, Prefiguring the Future: Benjamin Remembering His Childhood -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReaders once believed in Proust's madeleine and in Wordsworth's recollections of his boyhood-but that was before literary culture began to defer to Freud's questioning of adult memories of childhood. In this first sustained look at childhood memories as depicted in literature, Lorna Martens reveals how much we may have lost by turning our attention the other way. Her work opens a new perspective on early recollection-how it works, why it is valuable, and how shifts in our understanding are reflected in both scientific and literary writings.Science plays an important role in The Promise of Memory, which is squarely situated at the intersection of literature and psychology. Psychologists have made important discoveries about when childhood memories most often form, and what form they most often take. These findings resonate throughout the literary works of the three writers who are the focus of Martens' book. Proust and Rilke, writing in the modernist period before Freudian theory penetrated literary culture, offer original answers to questions such as "Why do writers consider it important to remember childhood? What kinds of things do they remember? What do their memories tell us?" In Walter Benjamin, Martens finds a writer willing to grapple with Freud, and one whose writings on childhood capture that struggle.For all three authors, places and things figure prominently in the workings of memory. Connections between memory and materiality suggest new ways of understanding not just childhood recollection but also the artistic inclination, which draws on a childlike way of seeing: object-focused, imaginative, and emotionally intense.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aLiterature, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aMemory in literature. 0aModernism (Literature) 0aModernism (Literature). 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 70(DE-601)1054515760(DE-588)4163872-4aKindheitserinnerung2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2011z9783110261240oZDB-23-DGA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP Complete eBook Package 2011-2014z978311037488908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package 2011z978311037492608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220508iTitle is part of eBook p